  "prompt": "Is variance another word for standard deviation?",
  "response": "No, variance and standard deviation are not the same, although they are related concepts in statistics. \n\n- **Variance** is a measure of how much the values in a data set differ from the mean of that set. It is calculated as the average of the squared differences from the mean. \n\n- **Standard deviation** is the square root of the variance. It provides a measure of dispersion in the same units as the original data, making it more interpretable in many cases.\n\nIn summary, while both measure variability, variance is the square of the standard deviation.",
